NTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book addresses the impact of globalization on the lives of youth, focusing on the role of legal institutions and discourses. As practices and ideas travel the globe-such as the promotion and transmission of zero tolerance and retributive justice programs, the near ubiquitous acceptance of the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child, and the transnational migration of street gangs-the legal arena is being transformed. The essays in this book offer case studies and in-depth analyses, spanning diverse settings including courts and prisons, inner-city streets, international human rights initiatives, newspaper offices, local youth organizations, and the United Nations. Drawing on everyday social practices, each chapter adds clarity to our current understanding of the ways in which ideas and practices in different parts of the world can affect youth in one particular locale.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspects. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration of. 0aSocial control. 0aYouthxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aYouthxSocial conditionsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aMurphy, Alexandra K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunting, Annie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoughlin, Brenda C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZilberg, Elana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeger Boyle, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuidry, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuncie, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.